Product Version     25.10    Cadence Design Systems, Inc.
verifyWireGap(25.10)                                      verifyWireGap(25.10)

Name
       verifyWireGap - Verifies the continuity of follow pin and stripes

Syntax
       verifyWireGap

       [-help]

       [-append]

       [-area {<x1 y1 x2 y2>}]

       [-layers <layer_names>]

       [-net <power_nets>]

       [-report <filename>]

       [-wireToBoundary [-chip {<v1 v2>}] [-core {<v1 v2>}] [-block {<v1 v2>}]
       [-powerdomain {<v1> <v2>}]]

        [-wireToShape [-ring <value>]]

       [-wireToWire <value>]

       Verifies  the continuity of follow pin and stripes. Use this command to
       identify power strap failures due to broken power wires  in  the  power
       planning  stage. The verifyWireGap command gives you the flexibility to
       check for breaks in a specific area and for specific  layers  or  power
       nets.

       Additionally, you can use this command to ensure that wires do not stop
       short of the expected distance from the chip, core, or block boundary.

Parameters
       -help  Prints  a  brief  description that includes the type and default
              information for each verifyWireGap parameter.

              For a detailed description of the command and  all  its  parame-
              ters, use the man command:

              man verifyWireGap

       -append
              Specifies that all previous verifyWireGap settings will be kept.

       -area {<x1 y1 x2 y2>}
              Specifies the area to be checked.

       -block {<v1 v2>}
              Specifies the wire-to-block gap distance. Here:

              *

                v1:  Specifies the threshold value or acceptable distance from
                the block boundary to the wire.

              *

                v2: Specifies how far to look from the block boundary to  find
                wires that should be considered for the check.

              Use this check to ensure that vertical straps cover the horizon-
              tal  straps  underneath  them near a block edge. For example, if
              you specify verifyWireGap -wireToBounday  -block  {0  0.3},  any
              wire that is at a distance less than 0.3um from the block bound-
              ary is reported as a violation. Wires that are at a greater dis-
              tance  than  0.3um  are not flagged as violations as such breaks
              are assumed to be intentional.

       -chip {<v1 v2>}
              Specifies the wire-to-chip boundary gap distance. Here:

              *

                v1: Specifies the threshold value or acceptable distance  from
                the chip boundary to the wire.

              *

                v2:  Specifies  how far to look from the chip boundary to find
                wires that should be considered for the check.

              For example, if you specify verifyWireGap  -wireToBounday  -chip
              {0 0.3}, any wire that is at a distance less than 0.3um from the
              chip  boundary  is  reported as a violation. Wires that are at a
              greater distance than 0.3um are not  flagged  as  violations  as
              such breaks are assumed to be intentional.

       -core {<v1 v2>}
              Specifies the wire-to-core boundary gap distance. Here:

              *

                v1:  Specifies the threshold value or acceptable distance from
                the core boundary to the wire.

              *

                v2: Specifies how far to look from the core boundary  to  find
                wires that should be considered for the check.

              For  example,  if you specify verifyWireGap -wireToBounday -core
              {0 0.3}, any wire that is at a distance less than 0.3um from the
              core boundary is reported as a violation. Wires that  are  at  a
              greater  distance  than  0.3um  are not flagged as violations as
              such breaks are assumed to be intentional.

       -layers <layer_names>
              Specifies the metal layers to be considered.

       -net <power_nets>
              Specifies the name of the power nets that will be checked.

       -powerdomain {<v1 v2>}
              Specifies the wire-to-power-domain gap distance. Here:

              *

                v1: Specifies the threshold value or acceptable distance  from
                the power domain to the wire.

              *

                v2:  Specifies  how  far to look from the power domain to find
                wires that should be considered for the check.

       -report <filename>
              Specifies the report file for verifyWireGap violations data.

       -ring <value>
              Specifies the wire-to-ring gap distance.

       -wireToBoundary
              Checks the wire to boundary gap. You must  specify  one  of  the
              following sub-options with -wireToBoundary:

              * -block to check the gap between wire and block boundary.

              * -chip to check the gap between wire and chip boundary.

              * -core to check the gap between wire and core boundary.

              * -powerdomain to check the gap between wire and power domain.

       -wireToShape
              Checks the gap between the wire and some specific shapes.

       -wireToWire <value>
              Specifies  the  wire-to-wire gap distance. Use this check to en-
              sure that wires do not stop short of another wire  of  the  same
              net  or  layer.  For  instance, you can use this check to ensure
              that wires connect properly to a power ring.

              If the wire-to-wire gap in the same net is less than the  speci-
              fied  threshold value, verifyWireGap flags it as a violation. If
              the wire-to-wire is greater than the threshold value, the  break
              is assumed to be intentional.

Example
       The  following  command  checks wire-to-wire gap and flags wires in the
       same net that are closer than 0.2um:

       verifyWireGap -wireToWire 0.2

Related Information
       The Identifying and Viewing Violations chapter of User Guide.

